# Generated by tools/generate-docs.py. Do not edit by hand.

DOCS = {
    'getSunrise': "The elevation-adjusted sunrise time. Computed using a geometric zenith of 90 degrees plus an elevation adjustment. The zenith is further adjusted to account for atmospheric refraction and the sun's radius, for a total of 90.83333 degrees before elevation adjustment. If the sun does not rise on a given day, the sunrise may not be available or cannot be calculated. The result is elevation adjusted.",
    'getSeaLevelSunrise': 'The time of sunrise calculated at sea level, without adjusting for elevation. Sunrise is computed without the elevation adjustment, so it reflects sea-level sunrise. This is the base for dawn calculations that are measured as a dip below the horizon before sunrise. The zman may not be available in places or on days where the sun does not rise, such as parts of the Arctic Circle.',
    'getBeginCivilTwilight': 'The beginning of civil twilight, also called dawn. Calculated using a zenith of 96 degrees. See [civil twilight](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twilight#Civil_twilight). If the calculation cannot be computed, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getBeginNauticalTwilight': 'The start of nautical twilight, when the sun is 102 degrees below the zenith. Calculated using a zenith of 102 degrees. More on nautical twilight: [Nautical twilight](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twilight#Nautical_twilight) If the calculation cannot be computed, this zman may not be available.',
    'getBeginAstronomicalTwilight': 'The start of astronomical twilight, when the sky is still very dark but twilight has begun. Calculated using a zenith of 108 degrees. If the calculation cannot be computed, this zman may not be available.',
    'getSunset': "The elevation-adjusted sunset time. Calculated using a geometric zenith of 90 degrees plus an elevation adjustment. The zenith is further adjusted to account for atmospheric refraction and the sun's radius, for a total of 90.83333 degrees. In some cases, the calculated sunset can occur before sunrise, usually when a time zone other than the local time zone is used. In that case, the sunset date is moved to the following date. If the sunset cannot be calculated, the zman may not be available.",
    'getSeaLevelSunset': 'The time of sunset calculated at sea level, without elevation adjustment. It is sunset with no elevation adjustment. This sea-level sunset is the base for dusk calculations, which are measured as a dip below the horizon after sunset. If sunset cannot be calculated, such as in the Arctic Circle on days when the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available. Non-sunrise and sunset calculations such as dawn and dusk depend on visible light, which is not affected by elevation.',
    'getEndCivilTwilight': 'The end of civil twilight, defined as the point when the sun is 96 degrees below the horizon. Calculated using a zenith of 96 degrees. Civil twilight is the twilight period described here: [civil twilight](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Twilight#Civil_twilight). If the calculation cannot be computed, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getEndNauticalTwilight': 'The end of nautical twilight. Calculated using a zenith of 102 degrees. If the calculation cannot be computed, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getEndAstronomicalTwilight': 'The end of astronomical twilight, when the sun is 108 degrees below the horizon. Calculated using a zenith of 108 degrees. If the calculation cannot be computed, this zman may not be available.',
    'getSunTransit': "Solar noon, also called sundial noon, the moment when the Sun crosses the celestial meridian. It is the Sun's transit across the celestial meridian. In normal cases it is calculated as astronomical noon. If solar noon cannot be calculated for a particular date and location, the zman may not be available. This is the proper definition of solar noon or midday. In some high-latitude locations, such as parts of the Arctic Circle, the zman may not be available on days when the Sun does not rise or does not set.",
    'getSolarMidnight': "Solar midnight is the end of the day, and it may fall after midnight on the civil date it is being calculated for. For example, solar midnight for February 8 refers to the midnight between February 8 and February 9. It is the time when the sun crosses the lower celestial meridian, also called solar nadir. It is based on the sun's lower transit at the end of the day. See [The Definition of Chatzos](https://kosherjava.com/2020/07/02/definition-of-chatzos/) for more detail on the definition of solar noon and midnight. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in some locations or on some dates where the needed transit time cannot be determined.",
    'getPlagHamincha120MinutesZmanis': 'The time of plag hamincha according to the 120-minute zmanis day. It is meant for stringency only. Calculated as 10.75 hours after dawn, using the 120-minute zmanis day length. This zman should be used lechumra only. It is based on an extremely early dawn and a very late tzais, so it can be a very late time and is often after shkiah. If the calculation cannot be computed in a given location or date, the zman may not be available. Using it leniently can lead to serious mistakes, including chillul Shabbos. Deprecated: this zman should be used lechumra only because it can be very late, often after shkiah, and using it leniently can result in serious halachic errors.',
    'getPlagHamincha120Minutes': 'Plag hamincha according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that starts at alos 120 minutes. Calculated as 10.75 shaah zmanis 120 minutes after alos 120 minutes. This is based on an extremely early alos and a very late tzais, so it returns a very late time, often after shkiah. It should be used lechumra only. The zman may not be available if it cannot be calculated, such as in locations where the sun does not rise on one day and does not set on another. Deprecated because it can return a very late time and, if used lekula, can lead to serious mistakes such as chillul Shabbos. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getAlos60Minutes': 'Dawn calculated as 60 minutes before sunrise. It is based on either actual sunrise or sea level sunrise, depending on whether elevation is used. 60 minutes before sunrise, or 60 minutes before sea level sunrise when elevation is not used. This is the time to walk 4 mil at 15 minutes per mil. The zman may not be available where the sun does not rise or does not set. Related to a 60-minute-based approach used for other zmanim.',
    'getAlos72Zmanis': "Alos, or dawn, calculated as 72 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise. It is calculated as sunrise based on elevation setting minus 1.2 times the GRA zmaniyos hour. This is the same as 1/10 of the day, based on 4 mil being 72 minutes. This calculation is based on an 18-minute mil and on the day running from sunrise to sunset. {uses_elevation} This calculation is used in the calendars published by the Hisachdus Harabanim D'Artzos Habris Ve'Canada. If the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.",
    'getAlos96Minutes': 'The time of alos, or dawn, calculated as 96 minutes before sunrise. If elevation is used, it is based on sunrise; otherwise it is based on sea level sunrise. It is set 96 minutes before sunrise, based on the time to walk 4 mil at 24 minutes per mil. This approach follows the view that the time between dawn and sunrise is fixed by the time it takes to walk 4 mil, not by season or location. The zman may not be available in places and times where sunrise cannot be calculated.',
    'getAlos90Zmanis': 'The time of alos, or dawn, calculated as 90 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise. It is calculated as sunrise minus 1.5 times the GRA shaah zmanis. Sunrise is taken as sea-level sunrise or elevation-adjusted sunrise, depending on the elevation setting. This is based on 4 mil of 22.5 minutes each, which equals 90 minutes, or 1/8 of a day. The zman may not be available in locations or on days where sunrise or sunset cannot be calculated, such as in the Arctic Circle. The source also references the elevation setting when determining which sunrise is used.',
    'getAlos96Zmanis': 'The time of alos (dawn) based on 96 zmaniyos minutes, which is 1/7.5 of the day before sunrise. It is calculated as sunrise based on the elevation setting minus 1.6 times shaah zmanis GRA. The day used for the calculation runs from sea level sunrise to sea level sunset, or from sunrise to sunset when elevation is used. 96 zmaniyos minutes equals 4 mil, using a 24-minute mil. This zman may not be available in places or on days where sunrise cannot be calculated, such as in the Arctic Circle. {uses_elevation}',
    'getAlos90Minutes': 'Calculates alos (dawn) as 90 minutes before sunrise, or sea level sunrise when elevation is used. This is based on the time it takes to walk 4 mil at 22.5 minutes per mil. {uses_elevation} The zman may not be available if the sun does not rise on that date.',
    'getAlos120Minutes': 'A very early dawn time, 120 minutes before sunrise, based on the 5 mil at 24 minutes per mil opinion. It is intended to be used only stringently, such as for stopping eating on a fast day, and not as the start of daytime mitzvos. 120 minutes before sunrise, or before sea level sunrise when elevation is not used, based on the time to walk 5 mil at 24 minutes per mil. {uses_elevation} Because this is an extremely early time, it should only be used stringently and not to begin mitzvos that can only be done during the day. In places such as the Arctic Circle, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. This zman should be used only stringently. It is deprecated to warn against using it leniently, since that can lead to doing daytime mitzvos too early according to most opinions.',
    'getAlos120Zmanis': 'Calculates alos (dawn) using 120 zmaniyos minutes, which is 1/6 of the day, before sunset. It is meant only for being strict, not as the start time for mitzvos that can only be done during the day. It is calculated as sunset minus 2 shaah zmanis based on the GRA. The day is measured from sea level sunrise to sea level sunset or from sunrise to sunset, depending on whether elevation is used. This zman should be used only lechumra, such as stopping to eat on a fast day. It is extremely early. If the calculation cannot be made, such as in places like the Arctic Circle where the sun may not rise or set on some days, the zman may not be available. This zman should be used only lechumra. Using it leniently can result in performing daytime mitzvos too early according to most opinions. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getAlos26Degrees': 'The time of alos (dawn) when the sun is 26 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. It is calculated using a degree-based approach equivalent to 120 minutes before sunrise around the equinox/equilux in Jerusalem, which works out to 26 degrees below geometric zenith. This is extremely early and should be used lechumra only, such as for stopping to eat on a fast day. It should not be used as the start time for mitzvos that can only be performed during the day. The zman may not be available if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, such as in locations near or beyond the Arctic and Antarctic Circles. See the detailed explanation in the AstronomicalCalendar documentation. [https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/) This zman is deprecated as a warning because it returns a very early time and can lead to doing mitzvos hayom too early if used leniently. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getAlos18Degrees': 'The time of alos, or dawn, when the sun is 18 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. It is calculated based on the sun being 18 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. At some northern and southern locations, including places even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach that position below the horizon.',
    'getAlos19Degrees': "Dawn (alos) when the sun is 19 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. This is identified as Rambam's alos according to Rabbi Moshe Kosower, Rabbi Yaakov Shakow, and the cited works. Calculated from when the sun is 19 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. In locations so far north or south that the sun does not reach 19 degrees below the horizon, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. Sources cited: [Maimonides](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maimonides), [Maaglei Tzedek](https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/145454098), [Ayeles Hashachar Vol. I](https://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=33464&pgnum=13), [Yom Valayla Shel Torah](https://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=55960&pgnum=258), and [Luach Ikvei Hayom](https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1043573513).",
    'getAlos19Point8Degrees': "Alos, or dawn, when the sun is 19.8 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. This is based on the same idea as 90 minutes before sunrise, but uses a degree-based calculation instead of a fixed time. It corresponds to the sun's position about 90 minutes before sunrise in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux, which works out to 19.8 degrees below geometric zenith. At some northern and southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, this zman may not be available because the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon for the calculation. See the [equinox vs equilux zmanim calculations](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/) discussion for the background behind this value.",
    'getMisheyakir12Point85Degrees': "A very early misheyakir time based on the sun being 12.85 degrees below geometric zenith. It is described as slightly later than 57 minutes before sunrise in Jerusalem around the equinox or equilux. It is intended only for bish'as hadchak. Calculated from the sun's position 12.85 degrees below geometric zenith. This zman may not be available in some far-north or far-south locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation. This zman is deprecated because it is very early and should only be used for bish'as hadchak. Lechatchila, a later zman should be used.",
    'getMisheyakir11Point5Degrees': 'The time of misheyakir when the sun is 11.5 degrees below geometric zenith. This is used by some opinions for determining misheyakir. Based on the sun being 11.5 degrees below geometric zenith, which corresponds to about 52 minutes before sunrise in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux. See [equilux discussion](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/). At some northern and southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon. This calculation is described as one used by some opinions.',
    'getMisheyakir11Degrees': 'The time of misheyakir based on the sun being 11 degrees below geometric zenith. This is used by some opinions for determining misheyakir. Calculated when the sun is 11 degrees below geometric zenith (90 degrees). This is described as being about 48 minutes before sunrise in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux, which matches the discussion in [Equinox vs Equilux Zmanim Calculations](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/). In some far northern or southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon.',
    'getMisheyakir10Point2Degrees': "The time of misheyakir when the sun is 10.2 degrees below geometric zenith. This is used by some opinions for determining misheyakir. It is calculated when the sun reaches 10.2 degrees below geometric zenith, which is described as being based on the sun's position about 45 minutes before sunrise in Jerusalem around the equinox. More detail is given in [equinox vs equilux zmanim calculations](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/). In northern and southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon.",
    'getMisheyakir7Point65Degrees': "The time of misheyakir when the sun is 7.65 degrees below geometric zenith. This is described as roughly a 35-36 minute zman around the equinox or equilux, when twilight is shortest, and reflects opinions that place misheyakir at about 35-40 minutes before sunrise or a little less than 8 degrees below the horizon. Calculated from the sun's position at 7.65 degrees below geometric zenith (90 degrees). In very northern or southern locations, including places even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, the zman may not be available because the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation.",
    'getMisheyakir9Point5Degrees': "Misheyakir when the sun is 9.5 degrees below geometric zenith (90 degrees). Calculated from the sun's position at 9.5 degrees below geometric zenith. This is based on Rabbi Dovid Kronglass's 45-minute calculation in Baltimore as cited in the source. This zman may not be available in northern or southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for the calculation. The source says this zman is also used in some published calendars and follows the view of Rabbi Shmuel Kamenetsky as described there.",
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA19Point8Degrees': 'The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the Magen Avraham approach using dawn at 19.8 degrees below sunrise. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is defined as 19.8 degrees before sunrise. At extreme northern or southern locations where the sun does not go low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA16Point1Degrees': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham view, using dawn that is 16.1 degrees before sunrise. It is calculated as 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 16.1 degrees below sunrise and the day is measured from dawn to nightfall. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, including some locations north of the Arctic Circle or south of the Antarctic Circle.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA18Degrees': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham, using 18 degrees dawn and 18 degrees nightfall. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 18 degrees before sunrise. If the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA72MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the Magen Avraham, using dawn that is 72 zmaniyos minutes before sea level sunrise. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 72 zmaniyos minutes before sea level sunrise. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places where the sun does not rise or does not set on some day of the year, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA90Minutes': 'The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the Magen Avraham, using dawn 90 minutes before sunrise as the start of the day. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 90 minutes before sunrise and the day is measured from that dawn to 90 minutes after sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places or on days where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA90MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using a day that starts 90 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise and ends 90 zmaniyos minutes after sunset. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after alos 90 zmaniyos. This zman may not be available when the calculation cannot be determined, such as in the Arctic Circle where there is at least one day each year when the sun does not rise and one when it does not set.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA96Minutes': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using a day that starts 96 minutes before sunrise and ends 96 minutes after sunset. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is defined as 96 minutes before sunrise. This zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations such as the Arctic Circle, where the sun may not rise or set on some days.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA96MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that starts 96 minutes zmaniyos before sunrise and ends 96 minutes zmaniyos after sunset. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where a shaah zmanis is one-twelfth of the zmaniyos day from 96 minutes zmaniyos before sunrise to 96 minutes zmaniyos after sunset. In locations such as the Arctic Circle, where the sun may not rise on some days or may not set on others, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanShma3HoursBeforeChatzos': 'The latest time to recite Shema in the morning, calculated using the Komarno-style view. It is calculated as 3 regular clock hours before chatzos hayom. This uses regular clock hours, not shaos zmaniyos. The calculation may not be available if it cannot be determined, such as in locations like the Arctic Circle where the sun may not rise or set on some days.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA120Minutes': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham, using a very early stringency that treats dawn as 120 minutes before sunrise. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is defined as 120 minutes before sunrise. This is an extremely early zman and is considered a chumra. The Magen Avraham opinion is based on a day measured from 120 minutes before sunrise to 120 minutes after sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in the Arctic Circle where the sun does not rise or does not set on certain days, the zman may not be available. See the [Magen Avraham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avraham_Gombiner).',
    'getSofZmanShmaAlos16Point1ToSunset': "The latest time to recite Shema in the morning, based on a day that begins at alos 16.1 degrees and ends at sea level sunset. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees, using the time span from alos 16.1 degrees to sea level sunset. This follows the opinion of Chidushei v'Klalos HaRaza and Minora HaTahora, as cited by Yisrael Vehazmanim. In locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.",
    'getSofZmanShmaAlos16Point1ToTzaisGeonim7Point083Degrees': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema, using a day that begins at alos 16.1 degrees and ends at tzais 7.083 degrees. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees, with the day measured from alos 16.1 degrees to tzais 7.083 degrees. If the sun does not reach the needed position below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA19Point8Degrees': 'The latest time for morning prayer according to the Magen Avraham view, using dawn at 19.8 degrees below the horizon as the start of the day. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, with dawn defined as 19.8 degrees before sunrise. This follows the opinion that the day runs from dawn to nightfall, with both measured at 19.8 degrees below sunrise or sunset. At very northern or southern locations, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA16Point1Degrees': 'The latest time for morning prayer according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using dawn at 16.1 degrees before sunrise. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, with dawn defined as 16.1 degrees before sunrise. The day is measured from dawn to nightfall, with both set at 16.1 degrees below sunrise or sunset. In locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. The documentation also refers to this as the latest zman krias shema.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA18Degrees': 'The latest time for morning prayer according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using dawn at 18 degrees before sunrise. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, with dawn defined as 18 degrees before sunrise. This follows the Magen Avraham view that the day runs from dawn to nightfall, with both at 18 degrees below sunrise or sunset. The zman may not be available in some northern and southern locations, including places even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA72MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time for morning prayers according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using dawn that is 72 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 72 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise and the day runs until nightfall 72 zmaniyos minutes after sunset. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places and seasons where sunrise or sunset do not occur. This follows the Magen Avraham view that the day is measured from dawn to nightfall, with both defined as 72 zmaniyos minutes from sunrise and sunset.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA90Minutes': 'The latest time to recite the morning prayers according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using dawn 90 minutes before sunrise and nightfall 90 minutes after sunset. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after 90-minute dawn, where the day is measured from 90 minutes before sunrise to 90 minutes after sunset. This follows the Magen Avraham ([MGA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avraham_Gombiner)) approach. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places such as the Arctic Circle on days when the sun does not rise or does not set.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA90MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time for morning prayers according to the Magen Avraham view, using a dawn that is 90 zmaniyos before sunrise and a nightfall that is 90 zmaniyos after sunset. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where each shaah zmanis is based on the day from that dawn to that nightfall. If the zman cannot be calculated, such as in places or times where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available. The documentation ties this calculation to a dawn of 90 zmaniyos before sunrise and a nightfall of 90 zmaniyos after sunset.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA96Minutes': 'The latest time to recite morning prayers according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using a day that begins 96 minutes before sunrise and ends 96 minutes after sunset. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after alos 96 minutes, with the day measured from 96 minutes before sunrise to 96 minutes after sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in locations and seasons with extreme daylight conditions, the zman may not be available.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA96MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time for morning prayers according to the Magen Avraham, using dawn 96 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise as the start of the day. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after alos that is 96 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise. This follows the view that the day runs from alos 96 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise until tzais 96 zmaniyos minutes after sunset. If the sun does not rise or set, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA120Minutes': 'The latest time to recite the morning prayers according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that begins 120 minutes before sunrise and ends 120 minutes after sunset. It is calculated as 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 120 minutes before sunrise and the day runs from that dawn until 120 minutes after sunset. This is an extremely early zman and is considered a chumra. In locations where sunrise or sunset cannot be determined, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanTfila2HoursBeforeChatzos': 'The latest zman tfila, based on calculating it as 2 hours before chatzos hayom. 2 hours before chatzos hayom. This follows the opinion that calculates sof zman krias shema as 3 hours before chatzos hayom. If the calculation cannot be made, such as in locations where the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available.',
    'getMinchaGedola30Minutes': 'Mincha gedola calculated as 30 minutes after chatzos. This is 30 minutes of regular clock time after chatzos, rather than half of a shaah zmanis after chatzos. Some people use this later start time for mincha in winter when half of a shaah zmanis is less than 30 minutes. You should not use this time to start mincha before the standard mincha gedola. Because it is a fixed 30 minutes after chatzos, it is affected by astronomical chatzos and not by the setting that governs other zmanim.',
    'getMinchaGedola72Minutes': 'The earliest time to pray mincha, calculated according to the Magen Avraham with the day beginning 72 minutes before sunrise and ending 72 minutes after sunset. Calculated as 6.5 solar hours after alos, using 72-minute day boundaries. When {use_astronomical_chatzos_for_other_zmanim}, it is based on a half-day-based shaah zmanis between chatzos and 72 minutes after chatzos. If the zman cannot be calculated, it may not be available. {use_astronomical_chatzos_for_other_zmanim}',
    'getMinchaGedola16Point1Degrees': 'The earliest time to pray mincha, calculated according to the Magen Avraham with the day starting and ending 16.1 degrees below the horizon. It is calculated as 6.5 solar hours after alos at 16.1 degrees below the horizon. {use_astronomical_chatzos_for_other_zmanim} The zman may not be available if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation.',
    'getMinchaGedolaAhavatShalom': "The earliest time to pray mincha, following the opinion of Rabbi Yaakov Moshe Hillel, as published by the Bais Horaah of Yeshivat Chevrat Ahavat Shalom. It is based on half a seasonal hour after chatzos. The seasonal hours are measured using a day that starts 72 minutes before sunrise and ends 13.5 minutes after sunset. The later of that time or 30 clock minutes after chatzos is used. See Rabbi Yaakov Moshe Hillel's [Wikipedia page](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yaakov_Moshe_Hillel) for background on the person named in the source. At some locations, especially far north or far south, the zman may not be available if the sun does not go low enough below the horizon for this calculation.",
    'getMinchaGedolaGRAGreaterThan30': 'The later mincha gedola time between the GRA calculation and 30 minutes after chatzos. Compares getMinchaGedolaGRA() with getMinchaGedola30Minutes() and returns the later one. In winter, when half of a shaah zmanis is less than 30 minutes, the 30-minute time is used; otherwise the GRA time is used. Because this can be based on a 30-minute offset from chatzos, the result may be affected by astronomical chatzos. If the calculation cannot be computed in a given location or date, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getMinchaKetana16Point1Degrees': 'The time of mincha ketana, calculated using the Magen Avraham day that begins and ends when the sun is 16.1 degrees below the horizon. It is described as the preferred earliest time to pray mincha according to the Rambam and others. It is calculated as 9.5 temporal hours after alos. More specifically, it is 9.5 shaah zmanis after alos at 16.1 degrees. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, including some northern and southern locations even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle.',
    'getMinchaKetanaAhavatShalom': 'Mincha ketana according to the opinion of Rabbi Yaakov Moshe Hillel, as published by the Bais Horaah of Yeshivat Chevrat Ahavat Shalom. It is the preferred earliest time to pray mincha according to the opinion of the Rambam and others. It is calculated as 2.5 shaos zmaniyos before tzais 3.8 degrees. The shaos zmaniyos are based on a day that starts at alos 16.1 degrees and ends at tzais 3.8 degrees. The zman may not be available if the calculation cannot be computed, such as in some far northern or southern locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon. See the discussion of mincha ketana GRA for more information.',
    'getMinchaKetana72Minutes': 'The time of mincha ketana according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that begins 72 minutes before sunrise and ends 72 minutes after sunset. This is the preferred earliest time to pray mincha according to the Rambam and others. It is calculated as 9.5 shaah zmanis of 72 minutes after alos, where alos is 72 minutes before sunrise. If sunrise or sunset cannot be determined, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getPlagHamincha60Minutes': 'The time of plag hamincha according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that starts 60 minutes before sunrise and ends 60 minutes after sunset. It is calculated as 10.75 shaah zmanis after dawn that is 60 minutes before sunrise. In other words, it is 10.75 seasonal hours after alos 60 minutes. If the zman cannot be calculated, such as in the Arctic Circle on a day when the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available.',
    'getPlagHamincha72Minutes': 'Plag hamincha according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that starts 72 minutes before sunrise and ends 72 minutes after sunset. It is calculated as 10.75 hours after dawn, using 10.75 shaos zmaniyos based on the 72-minute day. This zman should be used lechumra only, since it can fall after sunset. If the zman cannot be calculated, it may not be available. The documentation warns that using this zman leniently can lead to serious halachic problems such as chillul Shabbos. Deprecated. This zman should be used lechumra only, because it can be very late, often after shkiah.',
    'getPlagHamincha90Minutes': 'The time of plag hamincha according to the Magen Avraham, using a day that begins 90 minutes before sunrise and ends 90 minutes after sunset. It is calculated as 10.75 temporal hours after dawn that is 90 minutes before sunrise. This calculation can be very late, often after shkiah, so it should be used only lechumra. If the zman cannot be calculated, it may not be available. Since plag by this calculation can occur after sunset, using it lekula can lead to serious problems. Deprecated. It should be used only lechumra because it can return a very late time, often after shkiah, and using it lekula can result in chillul Shabbos. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getPlagHamincha96Minutes': 'The time of plag hamincha according to the Magen Avraham using a day that starts 96 minutes before sunrise and ends 96 minutes after sunset. It is 10.75 shaah zmanis after dawn at 96 minutes before sunrise. This calculation can place plag hamincha after sunset, so it should be used only as a stringency. The zman may not be available in places and seasons where sunrise or sunset cannot be calculated. Deprecated for use only as a stringency because it can give a very late time, often after shkiah, and using it leniently can lead to serious halachic errors. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getPlagHamincha96MinutesZmanis': 'The time of plag hamincha, calculated using 96-minute zmanis day hours starting from dawn. It is calculated as 10.75 hours after dawn, using 10.75 times the 96-minute zmanis hour measured from dawn. This zman should be used lechumra only. Because this calculation can fall after sunset, it should not be used lekula. If the zman cannot be calculated, for example in locations with periods when the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available. Deprecated as a warning that this zman can be very late, often after shkiah, and using it leniently can lead to serious halachic problems. It is not planned for removal.',
    'getPlagHamincha90MinutesZmanis': 'The time of plag hamincha, calculated using a 90-minute-zmanis day based on dawn 90 zmanis minutes before sunrise. It is calculated as 10.75 hours after dawn, using 10.75 times the 90-minute-zmanis shaah zmanis after dawn. This zman should be used lechumra only. Because this calculation can fall after sunset, using it leniently can create serious halachic problems. The zman may not be available in places such as the Arctic Circle on days when the sun does not rise or does not set. Deprecated to warn that it should be used lechumra only, because it can be very late and using it leniently can lead to serious problems; there is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getPlagHamincha72MinutesZmanis': 'The zman of plag hamincha, calculated using zemanios based on 72-minute dawn. It is calculated as 10.75 hours after dawn at 72 zmanis minutes, using 10.75 times the 72-minute zmanis hour. This zman should be used lechumra only, because this calculation can produce a very late time, often after shkiah, and using it leniently can lead to serious mistakes. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in locations where the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available. Deprecated. This zman should be used lechumra only because it can return a very late time, often after shkiah, and using it leniently can result in chillul Shabbos and other serious issues. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getPlagHamincha16Point1Degrees': 'The time of plag hamincha based on the day running from alos 16.1 degrees to tzais 16.1 degrees. It is calculated as 10.75 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees. This should be used lechumra only, since it can occur after sunset. At some extreme northern or southern locations, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. Deprecated for use only lechumra, because it can be a very late time and using it lekula can result in chillul Shabbos. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getPlagHamincha19Point8Degrees': 'The time of plag hamincha based on a day that starts at alos 19.8 degrees and ends at tzais 19.8 degrees. It is calculated as 10.75 proportional hours after alos 19.8 degrees, using the shaah zmanis for the 19.8-degree day. This zman should be used lechumra only. Because this calculation can be very late, it may occur after sunset and should not be used lekula. In some northern and southern locations, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. Deprecated: use this zman lechumra only, because it returns a very late time and using it lekula can lead to serious mistakes such as chillul Shabbos.',
    'getPlagHamincha26Degrees': 'The time of plag hamincha based on a day that starts at alos 26 degrees and ends at tzais 26 degrees. It is calculated as 10.75 zmaniyos hours after alos 26 degrees, using shaah zmanis 26 degrees. This zman should be used lechumra only because it is based on an extremely early alos and a very late tzais. It may not be available in places where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation. Deprecated because it should be used lechumra only; using it lekula can result in chillul Shabbos and similar problems.',
    'getPlagHamincha18Degrees': 'The time of plag hamincha based on a day that begins at alos 18 degrees and ends at tzais 18 degrees. It is calculated as 10.75 zmaniyos hours after alos 18 degrees, using the shaah zmanis for the 18-degree day. This zman should be used lechumra only, since it can occur after sunset. In some extreme northern or southern locations, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach far enough below the horizon. Deprecated. It is intended for lechumra only because it can be a very late time, and using it lekula can lead to serious problems such as chillul Shabbos. It is not planned to be removed.',
    'getPlagAlosToSunset': "This is a lechumra-only calculation of plag hamincha based on a day that begins at alos 16.1 degrees and ends at sunset. It is 10.75 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees, with the day's length measured from dawn at 16.1 degrees before sunrise to sea level sunset. Because this calculation can occur after sunset, it should only be used lechumra. In some places, such as locations near or beyond the polar circles, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. Deprecated. This zman should be used lechumra only because it can be very late, often after shkiah, and using it lekula can lead to serious mistakes.",
    'getPlagAlos16Point1ToTzaisGeonim7Point083Degrees': 'The time of plag hamincha based on a day that begins at 16.1 degrees before sunrise and ends at 7.083 degrees after sunset. It is 10.75 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees, using the day length from alos 16.1 degrees to tzais geonim 7.083 degrees. In some northern or southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, the zman may not be available because the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation.',
    'getPlagAhavatShalom': 'The time of plag hamincha according to Rabbi Yaakov Moshe Hillel, as published by the Bais Horaah of Yeshivat Chevrat Ahavat Shalom. It is the earliest time Shabbos can be started under this opinion. It is 1.25 shaos zmaniyos before tzais 3.8 degrees. The shaos zmaniyos are based on a day that begins at alos 16.1 degrees and ends at tzais 3.8 degrees. This follows the opinion of [Rabbi Yaakov Moshe Hillel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yaakov_Moshe_Hillel). The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, including some locations north of the Arctic Circle and south of the Antarctic Circle.',
    'getBainHashmashosRT13Point24Degrees': "The start of Rabbeinu Tam's bain hashmashos, when the sun is 13.24 degrees below the western geometric horizon after sunset. It is based on the same approach as Rabbeinu Tam's 58.5-minute bain hashmashos, but uses a degree-based threshold instead of an exact time. The 13.24-degree figure comes from the sun's position 58.5 minutes after sunset in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux. The source notes that a dip of slightly less than 13 degrees should be used, and that 13.24 degrees is a truncated value that is about 1.5 seconds earlier for leniency. This zman may not be available in locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for the calculation.",
    'getBainHashmashosRT58Point5Minutes': "The start of Rabbeinu Tam's bain hashmashos, calculated as 58.5 minutes after sunset. Computed as 3.25 mil after sunset. Using 18 minutes per mil, that works out to 58.5 minutes after sunset. Bain hashmashos is described here as 3/4 of a mil before tzais or 3 1/4 mil after sunset. If the zman cannot be calculated, such as in locations where the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available. See detailed explanation on top of the AstronomicalCalendar documentation.",
    'getBainHashmashosRT13Point5MinutesBefore7Point083Degrees': "The start of Rabbeinu Tam's bain hashmashos according to this calculation. It is calculated as 13.5 minutes before shkiah, using 7.083 degrees for tzais. The zman may not be available in very northern or southern locations, including places that are south of the Arctic Circle or north of the Antarctic Circle, where the sun may not go low enough below the horizon for this calculation.",
    'getBainHashmashosRT2Stars': 'The beginning of bain hashmashos of Rabbeinu Tam, calculated according to the Divrei Yosef view. It is calculated as 5/18 of the time between alos (defined here as 19.8 degrees before sunrise) and sunrise, and that amount is added to sunset. This calculation may not be available in northern and southern locations even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, where the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon for it to be calculated.',
    'getBainHashmashosYereim18Minutes': 'The beginning of bain hashmashos (twilight) according to the Yereim, which is taken to be 18 minutes before sunset. Calculated as 18 minutes, or 3/4 of a 24-minute mil, before sunset. According to the Yereim (Rabbi Eliezer of Metz), bain hashmashos begins 3/4 of a mil before sunset, and tzais (nightfall) starts at sunset. If the zman cannot be calculated, such as in places with extreme daylight patterns, it may not be available. Yereim (Rabbi Eliezer of Metz): https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eliezer_ben_Samuel Mil: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biblical_and_Talmudic_units_of_measurement',
    'getBainHashmashosYereim3Point05Degrees': "The beginning of Yereim bain hashmashos, calculated using the sun being 3.05 degrees above the horizon. Calculated as 18 minutes, or 3/4 of a 24-minute mil, before sunset. It uses a refraction value of 0.5166 degrees. According to the Yereim, bain hashmashos begins 3/4 of a mil before sunset, and tzais or nightfall starts at sunset. This degree-based calculation is noted as being around the equinox or equilux. For more details, see [The Yereim's Bain Hashmashos](https://kosherjava.com/2020/12/07/the-yereims-bein-hashmashos/).",
    'getBainHashmashosYereim16Point875Minutes': "The start of Yereim's bain hashmashos (twilight), calculated as 16.875 minutes before sunset. It is taken as 3/4 of a 22.5-minute mil before sunset. In Yereim's view, bain hashmashos begins 3/4 of a mil before sunset, and nightfall begins at sunset. This zman may not be available when the calculation cannot be made, such as in places and times where the sun does not rise or does not set. Yereim is Rabbi Eliezer of Metz: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eliezer_ben_Samuel Mil: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biblical_and_Talmudic_units_of_measurement",
    'getBainHashmashosYereim2Point8Degrees': "The start of bain hashmashos (twilight) according to the Yereim, calculated when the sun is 2.8 degrees above the horizon around the equinox or equilux. This is also described as 16.875 minutes, or 3/4 of an 18-minute mil, before sunset. It is based on the Yereim's view that bain hashmashos begins 3/4 of a mil before sunset, with tzais or nightfall at sunset. The 2.8 degrees figure is the way this timing is expressed around the equinox or equilux. If the zman cannot be computed, such as in places like the Arctic Circle where the sun may not rise or set on some days, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. Details on how the degrees were calculated are referenced in the documentation for the 3.05 degrees version of this zman.",
    'getBainHashmashosYereim13Point5Minutes': 'The beginning of bain hashmashos (twilight) according to the Yereim, set 13.5 minutes before sunset. Calculated as 13.5 minutes, or 3/4 of an 18-minute mil, before sunset. According to the Yereim, bain hashmashos begins 3/4 of a mil before sunset, and nightfall starts at sunset. In locations or situations where sunset cannot be computed, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getBainHashmashosYereim2Point1Degrees': "The beginning of bain hashmashos according to the Yereim, based on the sun being 2.1 degrees above the horizon in Yerushalayim around the equinox/equilux. It is based on the sun's position 2.1 degrees above the horizon, which the source describes as about 13.5 minutes, or 3/4 of an 18-minute mil, before sunset. According to the Yereim, bain hashmashos starts 3/4 of a mil before sunset and tzais, or nightfall, starts at sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in regions where the sun does not rise or does not set on some days, the zman may not be available.",
    'getTzaisGeonim3Point7Degrees': "Nightfall according to the Geonim, when the sun is 3.7 degrees below sea level. Calculated as the time when the sun reaches 3.7 degrees below geometric zenith, which is described as about 13.5 minutes after sunset. The documentation notes that this angle matches the sun's position in Jerusalem around the equinox or equilux. Deprecated.",
    'getTzaisGeonim3Point8Degrees': "The time of tzais, or nightfall, according to the Geonim when the sun is 3.8 degrees below sea level. Calculated when the sun reaches 3.8 degrees below geometric zenith (90 degrees below the horizon). This is described as about 13.5 minutes after sunset, or 14 minutes after sunset when using the stated mil-based estimate. In Jerusalem, this angle occurs around the equinox/equilux. See [Biblical and Talmudic units of measurement](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biblical_and_Talmudic_units_of_measurement) and [Equinox vs Equilux Zmanim Calculations](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/). This zman is based on the Geonim's view of nightfall. The source also describes it as the position of the sun 13.5 minutes after sunset, based on 3/4 of a mil at 18 minutes per mil plus 30 seconds for 49 amos. This zman is deprecated.",
    'getTzaisGeonim5Point95Degrees': 'Nightfall according to the Geonim, based on the sun being 5.95 degrees below geometric zenith. Calculated when the sun reaches 5.95 degrees below geometric zenith (90 degrees), which is described as about 24 minutes after sunset in Jerusalem around the equinox or equilux. This zman may not be available in far northern or far southern locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation. Chabad calendars usually use the 6-degree-based tzais Baal Hatanya, which is built on the same calculation.',
    'getTzaisGeonim4Point66Degrees': 'Nightfall according to the Geonim, based on the sun being 4.66 degrees below the western horizon. Calculated as 3/4 of a mil using a 24-minute mil, which is 18 minutes. This is a very early zman and should not be relied on without Rabbinical guidance. It does not include the additional 35.28 seconds needed to walk 49 amos, the heref ayin of bain hashmashos of Rav Yosi, at the pace of a 24-minute mil. This zman may not be available in northern and southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, where the sun may not reach far enough below the horizon for this calculation. Deprecated.',
    'getTzaisGeonim4Point42Degrees': 'Tzais (nightfall) according to the Geonim, at a very early point in the evening. It is based on the sun being 4.42 degrees below the western horizon. Based on 3/4 of a mil, using a 22.5-minute mil, which is 16 7/8 minutes. This is a very early zman and should not be relied on without rabbinical guidance. The zman may not be available in locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation. A related source notes that Rabbi Yedidya Manet lists 4.37 degrees, which appears to be slightly too early. Deprecated.',
    'getTzaisGeonim4Point8Degrees': 'Tzais (nightfall) according to the Geonim, set for when the sun is 4.8 degrees below the western horizon. This zman is based on 18.6 minutes after sunset, which is described as 3/4 of a 24-minute mil plus 0.6 minutes for bain hashmashos of Rav Yosi. This is an early zman for tzais and should not be relied on without Rabbinical guidance. At this point, 3 medium sized stars are visible to a non-expert with good vision with effort. An expert knowing where to look can see the 3 medium stars as early as 15 minutes after sunset. In some locations, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach the needed position below the horizon.',
    'getTzaisGeonim6Point45Degrees': "Nightfall according to the Geonim, using Rabbi Yechiel Michel Tucazinsky's 6.45 degrees below sea level sunset approach. It is commonly used in Israel and is also used in the Luach Itim Lebinah. Calculated for the time when the sun is 6.45 degrees below sea level. Based on Rabbi Yechiel Michel Tucazinsky's calculation as described in the Birur Halacha Yoreh Deah 262. See [Rabbi Yechiel Michel Tucazinsky](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yechiel_Michel_Tucazinsky), [Birur Halacha Yoreh Deah 262](https://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=50536&st=&pgnum=51), and [Luach Itim Lebinah](https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/243303103). At some northern and southern locations, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach the required position below the horizon. This 6.45 degree calculation differs from the 6.1 degree / 6.2 degree calculation associated with Rabbi Tucazinsky's time in Hazmanim Bahalacha Vol. II, chapter 50:7.",
    'getTzaisGeonim7Point083Degrees': "Nightfall according to the Geonim, based on the sun being 7.083 degrees below the western horizon. Calculated for when the sun is 7.083 degrees below sea level. This is based on the observation of three medium-sized stars by Dr. Baruch (Berthold) Cohn in his luach Tables containing the time listings for the beginning of night and day for latitudes +66 to -38, published in Strasbourg in 1899. It is often referred to as 7 degrees 5 minutes. It is close to the time of the Source of Kindness of Sefer Chasidim. It is close to the sun's position 30 minutes after sunset in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux, but not exactly the same. The actual position of the sun 30 minutes after sunset in Jerusalem at the equilux is 7.205 degrees and 7.199 degrees at the equinox. In some locations, such as far north or far south areas where the sun does not get low enough below the horizon, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.",
    'getTzaisGeonim7Point67Degrees': "Tzais, or nightfall, according to the Geonim, using the point where the sun is 7.75 degrees below the western horizon. It is based on 45 minutes after sunset during the summer solstice in New York, when twilight is longest. This zman may not be available in very northern or southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for the calculation. See Igros Moshe Even Haezer 4, Ch. 4, and Rabbi Heber's Shaarei Zmanim.",
    'getTzaisGeonim9Point3Degrees': 'Nightfall based on the stringent tzais timing used in the Luach Itim Lebinah. When the sun is 9.3 degrees below the western horizon. This zman may not be available in northern and southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon. Based on the calculations used in the Luach Itim Lebinah: [Luach Itim Lebinah](https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/243303103).',
    'getTzaisGeonim9Point75Degrees': "Nightfall according to the Geonim, based on the sun being 9.75 degrees below the western horizon. It is described as corresponding to about 60 minutes after sunset around the equinox or equilux, and is associated with the views of Rabbi Eliyahu Henkin and Rabbi Shmuel Kamenetsky. Calculated from the sun's position when it is 9.75 degrees below the western horizon. This timing may not be available in some northern or southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle or north of the Antarctic Circle, if the sun does not reach the required depth below the horizon. The source also notes that this corresponds to about 60 minutes after sunset around the equinox or equilux, when a solar hour is 60 minutes in New York.",
    'getTzais60Minutes': 'Tzais, or nightfall, defined as 60 minutes after sunset. This follows the opinion that a mil is walked in 15 minutes, for a total of 60 minutes after 4 mil. 60 minutes after sunset or sea level sunset, depending on the elevation setting. This zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places such as the Arctic Circle where there are days when the sun does not rise or does not set. See the detailed explanation of the 60-minute concept at getAlos60Minutes(). The source cites the Chavas Yair and Divrei Malkiel, and refers to a mil as a distance unit. For background, see [Chavas Yair](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yair_Bacharach), [Divrei Malkiel](https://he.wikipedia.org/wiki/%D7%9E%D7%9C%D7%9B%D7%99%D7%90%D7%9C_%D7%A6%D7%91%D7%99_%D7%98%D7%A0%D7%A0%D7%91%D7%95%D7%99%D7%9D), and [mil](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biblical_and_Talmudic_units_of_measurement).',
    'getTzaisAteretTorah': 'Tzais according to the Ateret Torah approach, usually 40 minutes after sunset. Calculated as 40 minutes after sea level sunset by default, with the offset configurable to a different number of minutes. Chacham Yosef Harari-Raful of Yeshivat Ateret Torah used this time only for other zmanim such as Sof Zman Krias Shema and Plag Hamincha; his calendars do not publish a zman for tzais. He also provided a 25-minute zman for Israel, but this documentation uses 40 minutes year round anywhere in the world by default. The zman may not be available in places and times where sunset cannot be calculated, such as the Arctic Circle.',
    'getSofZmanShmaAteretTorah': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Ateret Torah calculation. It is calculated using a day that starts 1/10 of the day before sunrise and usually ends 40 minutes after sunset, with the sunset offset configurable. The daily hour-length is based on that day, and the result is 3 temporal hours after alos 72 zmaniyos. Based on this calculation, chatzos will not be at midday. The sunset ending of the day is usually 40 minutes after sunset, but the offset can be changed. If the calculation cannot be computed, the zman may not be available.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaAteretTorah': 'The latest time for reciting the morning prayers according to the Ateret Torah calculation. This time is based on a day that starts 1/10th of the day before sunrise and usually ends 40 minutes after sunset, with the sunset offset configurable. Temporal hours are calculated from that day and added to alos 72 zmaniyos. It is 4 temporal hours after alos 72 zmaniyos. Based on this calculation, chatzos will not be at midday. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations such as the Arctic Circle, where the sun does not rise on some days and does not set on others.',
    'getMinchaGedolaAteretTorah': 'The time of mincha gedola according to the Ateret Torah calculation, which is the preferred earliest time to pray mincha according to the Rambam and others. It is calculated as 6.5 solar hours after alos. In this approach, the day begins 1/10 of the day before sunrise and usually ends 40 minutes after sunset, though the sunset offset can be set to a different value. The calculation uses alos 72 zmanis and tzais Ateret Torah. If sunrise or sunset cannot be determined, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. The Ateret Torah sunset offset is usually 40 minutes after sunset, but it can be configured to any offset.',
    'getMinchaKetanaAteretTorah': 'The time of mincha ketana according to the Ateret Torah calculation, used as the preferred earliest time to pray mincha according to the opinion of the Rambam and others. It is calculated as 9.5 solar hours after alos 72 zmanis. In this calculation, the day starts 1/10 of the day before sunrise and is usually considered to end 40 minutes after sunset, with that sunset offset configurable. The sunset offset used in the Ateret Torah calculation can be changed to any offset. The zman may not be available if the calculation cannot be computed, such as in locations with extreme polar conditions.',
    'getPlagHaminchaAteretTorah': 'The time of plag hamincha based on the Ateret Torah calculation. This is calculated using Ateret Torah day boundaries: the day starts 1/10th of the day before sunrise and usually ends 40 minutes after sunset, though the sunset offset can be adjusted. The shaos zmaniyos for that day are then used, and plag hamincha is 10.75 shaos zmaniyos after alos 72 zmaniyos. The sunset offset used for the Ateret Torah day can be configured to a different value. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places such as the Arctic Circle on days when the sun does not rise or does not set.',
    'getTzais72Zmanis': "Returns tzais (dusk) as 72 zmaniyos minutes, or one-tenth of the day after sea level sunset. This is the time used by the Minchas Cohen in Ma'amar 2:4 for Rebbeinu Tam's tzeis. It is calculated as 72 zmaniyos minutes after sea level sunset, which is equivalent to one-tenth of the day after sunset. This calculation can produce different clock-minute gaps from sunset to tzais throughout the year: about 72 clock minutes at the equinox, shortest at the winter solstice, and longest at the summer solstice. The source notes that this does not match reality because twilight is not directly tied to day length. The [Minchas Cohen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abraham_Cohen_Pimentel) in Ma'amar 2:4 uses this approach for Rebbeinu Tam's tzeis. If the calculation cannot be computed, the zman may not be available.",
    'getTzais90Zmanis': 'Calculates tzais (dusk) as 90 minutes zmaniyos, or one-eighth of the day, after sea level sunset. This is known in Yiddish as the achtel zman used in various kehilos. Add 90 minutes zmaniyos, or one-eighth of the day, to sea level sunset. The zman may not be available in locations such as the Arctic Circle, where there can be days when the sun does not rise and days when it does not set.',
    'getTzais96Zmanis': 'The time of tzais, or dusk, based on 96 zmaniyos minutes after sea level sunset. Calculated as 96 zmaniyos minutes, or 1/7.5 of the day, after sea level sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places like the Arctic Circle where the sun does not rise or does not set on certain days, the zman may not be available.',
    'getTzais90Minutes': "Tzais, or nightfall, 90 minutes after sunset. This is calculated as 90 minutes after sunset, using sea level sunset when elevation is not used and sunset when elevation is used. The 90 minutes come from the Magen Avraham's approach: 5 mil after sunset, with each mil treated as 18 minutes based on the Rambam's opinion. A similar calculation, tzais 19.8 degrees, uses solar position calculations based on this time. If the calculation cannot be computed, the zman may not be available.",
    'getTzais120Minutes': "Returns tzais (nightfall) based on a very late 120-minute calculation. It is intended for lechumra use only, such as delaying the start of nighttime mitzvos. It is based on Rav Chaim Naeh's calculation that the time to walk 1 mil is 24 minutes, for a total of 120 minutes after sunset. The calculation follows Ula's view of tzais as 5 mil after sunset or sea level sunset, depending on elevation. This zman is extremely late and is past the 18 degrees point where the darkest point is reached, so it should only be used lechumra. The zman may not be available in places and times where it cannot be calculated, such as the Arctic Circle. Deprecated because it is a very late time and using it lekula can lead to serious halachic problems such as chillul Shabbos. It is not planned to be removed.",
    'getTzais120Zmanis': 'This is a very late tzais (dusk) time, calculated as 120 zmaniyos minutes after sea level sunset. Sea level sunset plus 120 zmaniyos minutes. This zman is intended for lechumra only, such as delaying the start of nighttime mitzvos. Because it is extremely late and the sun is well below 18 degrees in most places, it should not be used lekula. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations or seasons where sunset cannot be determined, such as parts of the Arctic Circle. This zman is deprecated as a warning that it should be used lechumra only. Using it lekula can result in chillul Shabbos and other serious errors. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getTzais16Point1Degrees': "Tzais when the sun is 16.1 degrees below the horizon. This corresponds to Rabbeinu Tam's 72-minute tzais around the equinox/equilux in Jerusalem. It is based on the sun reaching 16.1 degrees below the horizon. The documentation notes that this lines up with 72 minutes after sunset according to Rabbeinu Tam's calculation around the equinox/equilux in Jerusalem. The documentation links this discussion of equinox vs equilux: [around the equinox / equilux](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/). Some authorities in the source material favor using the astronomical equinox, while others favor the equilux; the difference is about 9 seconds. The zman may not be available at very high latitudes where the sun does not reach 16.1 degrees below the horizon.",
    'getTzais26Degrees': 'The time of tzais when the sun is 26 degrees below the horizon. Calculated based on the sun reaching 26 degrees below the horizon. This zman is extremely late and should be used lechumra only, for example to delay the start of nighttime mitzvos. Using it lekula can lead to serious halachic problems, including chillul Shabbos. In some extreme locations, such as very far north or south, this zman may not be available because the sun may not reach that low below the horizon. Deprecated. This zman should be used lechumra only because it is very late and can be dangerous if used lekula. There is no current plan to remove it.',
    'getTzais18Degrees': 'The time of tzais at 18 degrees below the horizon. Calculated using the same 18-degree method described for alos 18 degrees, but for the evening when the sun is 18 degrees below the horizon. At some northern and southern locations, even those south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, this zman may not be available because the sun may not reach 18 degrees below the horizon.',
    'getTzais19Point8Degrees': 'The time of tzais calculated using the 19.8-degree standard. See the notes for alos 19.8 degrees; this zman uses the same 19.8-degree basis. At northern and southern locations even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, where the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available.',
    'getTzais96Minutes': 'Tzais, or dusk, calculated as 96 minutes after sunset. It is calculated as 96 minutes after sunset, or after sea level sunset if elevation is not used. {uses_elevation} This zman may not be available if it cannot be calculated, such as in locations like the Arctic Circle where the sun may not rise or may not set on certain days.',
    'getFixedLocalChatzosHayom': "The local fixed chatzos - solar noon adjusted for your location's longitude. At longitude 0, 15, 30, and so on, it is exactly 12:00 noon. This follows the Aruch Hashulchan in [Orach Chaim 233:14](https://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=7705&pgnum=426) and Rabbi Moshe Feinstein in Igros Moshe [Orach Chaim 1:24](https://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=916&st=&pgnum=67) and [2:20](https://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=14675&pgnum=191). It is based on 15 degrees per hour, or 4 minutes per degree, and the result is shifted by the difference between the location's longitude and the nearest 15-degree multiple. It also adjusts to the actual time zone and daylight saving time. For example, Lakewood, New Jersey, at longitude -74.222, is 0.778 degrees from -75 degrees, which gives a chatzos of 11:56:53. This is the fixed local chatzos, not a simple 12:00 noon clock time everywhere.",
    'getSofZmanKidushLevanaBetweenMoldos': "The latest time for Kiddush Levana according to the Maharil's view, which is based on the halfway point between one molad and the next. It is found by adding half of the 29 days, 12 hours and 793 chalakim between molad and molad - that is, 14 days, 18 hours, 22 minutes and 666 milliseconds - to the month's molad. This zman will be returned even if it occurs during the day. If the computed time falls between alos and tzais, alos is used. If the zman does not occur on that day, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. This follows the Maharil's opinion: [Yaakov ben Moshe Levi Moelin](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yaakov_ben_Moshe_Levi_Moelin).",
    'getSofZmanKidushLevana15Days': 'The latest time for Kiddush Levana, based on 15 days after the molad. This follows the opinion of the Shulchan Aruch (Orach Chaim 426). Calculated as 15 days after the molad. Some authorities hold a different view, associated with the Rema and the Maharil, which uses the time halfway between one molad and the next. The sof zman Kiddush Levana is returned even if it occurs during the day. If the time does not occur on that day, it may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getTchilasZmanKidushLevana3Days': 'The earliest time for Kiddush Levana according to Rabbeinu Yonah, who holds that it can be said 3 days after the molad. It is the moment 3 days after the molad. The time is returned even if it falls during the day, when Kiddush Levana cannot be said. Use the night-hours version if you want to limit the time to nighttime. The zman may not be available if it does not occur on that day.',
    'getZmanMolad': 'The moment of the molad, if it occurs on that day. If the molad does not occur on that day, the zman may not be available. Returns the time of the molad as an instant for the current day. See also JewishCalendar.getMoladAsInstant() for the traditional day of week, hour, minute, and chalakim.',
    'getTchilasZmanKidushLevana7Days': 'The earliest time for Kiddush Levana according to the opinion that it should not be said until 7 days after the molad. 7 days after the molad. This time is given even if it falls during the day, when Kiddush Levana cannot be recited. If you want to limit the time to night hours, use getTchilasZmanKidushLevana7Days(Instant, Instant). If the zman will not occur on this day, the zman may not be available.',
    'getSofZmanAchilasChametzGRA': "The latest time one may eat chametz on Erev Pesach according to the GRA. This time is 4 hours into the day based on the GRA's view that the day runs from sunrise to sunset. It is calculated as 4 shaah zmanis after sea level sunrise. This is identical to Sof zman tfilah GRA and is provided as a convenience for those who are unaware how it is calculated. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. The time may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations where the sun does not rise or does not set.",
    'getSofZmanAchilasChametzMGA72Minutes': 'The latest time to eat chametz according to the Magen Avraham view, using the 72-minute alos and 72-minute tzais day. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after alos, where alos is 72 minutes before sunrise and the day runs until 72 minutes after sunset. This is identical to sof zman tfilah according to the Magen Avraham with 72-minute day boundaries. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. The time may not be available or cannot be calculated in places or on days where sunrise or sunset does not occur.',
    'getSofZmanAchilasChametzMGA72MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time chametz may be eaten according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using a 72-zmaniyos-minute dawn before sunrise. This is the same time as sof zman tfila according to MGA 72 minutes zmanis. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is defined as 72 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. If the calculation cannot be made in extreme locations such as the Arctic Circle, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. This zman is based on the Magen Avraham view that the day runs from dawn 72 zmaniyos minutes before sunrise to nightfall 72 zmaniyos minutes after sunset.',
    'getSofZmanAchilasChametzMGA16Point1Degrees': 'The latest time chametz may be eaten on Erev Pesach according to the Magen Avraham approach using dawn 16.1 degrees before sunrise. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees, with the day measured from dawn to nightfall using 16.1 degrees below sunrise and sunset. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. The zman may not be available if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, such as in some locations far north or south. Uses the Magen Avraham view of the day from dawn to nightfall.',
    'getSofZmanBiurChametzGRA': "The latest time for burning chametz according to the GRA's calculation of the day from sunrise to sunset. It is 5 shaah zmanis GRA after sea level sunrise, which is 5 hours into the day by the GRA's sunrise-to-sunset day length. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. The time may not be available or cannot be calculated if sunrise and sunset cannot be determined, such as in locations where the sun does not rise or set on a given date.",
    'getSofZmanBiurChametzMGA72Minutes': 'The latest time to burn chametz, based on the Magen Avraham view using dawn 72 minutes before sunrise and nightfall 72 minutes after sunset. It is 5 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where dawn is 72 minutes before sunrise and the length of a shaah zmanis is based on the day from that dawn to nightfall 72 minutes after sunset. A value will always be returned, even if that day is not Erev Pesach. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places and times where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available.',
    'getSofZmanBiurChametzMGA72MinutesZmanis': 'The latest time to burn chametz on Erev Pesach according to the Magen Avraham approach using zmanis minutes. It is 5 shaos zmaniyos after alos, where alos is 72 zmanis minutes before sunrise. This is based on a day measured from 72 zmanis minutes before sunrise until 72 zmanis minutes after sunset. A value will always be returned, even if that day is not Erev Pesach. If the calculation cannot be made, such as in places like the Arctic Circle where sunrise or sunset may not occur, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanBiurChametzMGA16Point1Degrees': 'The latest time to burn chametz, calculated according to the Magen Avraham (MGA) using dawn at 16.1 degrees before sunrise. It is 5 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, where both dawn and nightfall are defined as 16.1 degrees below sunrise or sunset. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, such as some places near and beyond the Arctic and Antarctic Circles.',
    'getAlosBaalHatanya': "The Baal Hatanya's alos, or dawn. It is calculated as the time when the sun is 16.9 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. This is based on the idea that the time between dawn and netz amiti (sunrise) is 72 minutes, the time needed to walk 4 mil at 18 minutes per mil. In Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux, 72 minutes before sunrise corresponds to 16.9 degrees below geometric zenith. Based on the [Baal Hatanya](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shneur_Zalman_of_Liadi) calculation. The explanation references [Rambam](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maimonides) and others. This calculation may not be available in locations such as far north or far south where the sun may not reach far enough below the horizon. See the detailed explanation on top of the AstronomicalCalendar documentation. Additional background: [equinox vs equilux zmanim calculations](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/).",
    'getSofZmanShmaBaalHatanya': "The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the Baal Hatanya. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after netz amiti (sunrise) using the Baal Hatanya's day length, which is calculated from sunrise to sunset. If the zman cannot be calculated, for example in places where the sun does not rise or does not set on some days, the zman may not be available. See detailed explanation on top of the AstronomicalCalendar documentation.",
    'getSofZmanTfilaBaalHatanya': 'The latest time for morning prayers according to the Baal Hatanya, calculated as 4 hours into the day from sunrise to sunset. 4 shaos zmaniyos after Baal Hatanya sunrise (netz amiti). In places where sunrise or sunset cannot be determined, this zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanAchilasChametzBaalHatanya': "The latest time one may eat chametz according to the Baal Hatanya opinion. It is the same time as Sof zman tfilah Baal Hatanya, and a value is returned even on days that are not Erev Pesach. It is 4 hours into the day according to the Baal Hatanya approach, which measures the day from sunrise to sunset. It is calculated as 4 shaah zmanis after sunrise. Based on the Baal Hatanya's sunrise-to-sunset day. This zman may not be available if it cannot be calculated, such as in locations with extreme seasonal daylight conditions.",
    'getSofZmanBiurChametzBaalHatanya': "The latest time to burn chametz according to the Baal Hatanya's view of the day. It is 5 halachic hours after Baal Hatanya sunrise (netz amiti). The halachic hour used is the Baal Hatanya shaah zmanis, based on a day measured from sunrise to sunset. A value will always be returned, even if the day is not Erev Pesach. If the time cannot be calculated because the sun does not rise or set on that day, the zman may not be available.",
    'getMinchaGedolaBaalHatanya': "The time of mincha gedola, the earliest time one can pray mincha. In this view, mincha may be prayed lechatchila starting at mincha gedola. It is calculated as 6.5 shaah zmanis after netz amiti (real sunrise), using the Baal Hatanya's approach that the day runs from sunrise to sunset. The Rambam is quoted as preferring to delay mincha until mincha ketana. If the calculation cannot be done, such as in locations and times where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available.",
    'getMinchaKetanaBaalHatanya': "The preferred earliest time to pray mincha, according to the view of the Rambam and others. It is calculated as 9.5 sea level solar hours after sunrise, using the Baal Hatanya's view that the day runs from sunrise to sunset. If the time cannot be calculated, such as in places where the sun does not rise or set on certain days, the zman may not be available.",
    'getPlagHaminchaBaalHatanya': "The time of plag hamincha according to the Baal Hatanya's calculation of the day from sunrise to sunset. It is calculated as 10.75 seasonal hours after sunrise, using netz amiti. This calculation is based on the Baal Hatanya's opinion that the day is measured from sunrise to sunset. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places such as the Arctic Circle on days when the sun does not rise or does not set.",
    'getTzaisBaalHatanya': 'Nightfall according to the Baal Hatanya, when the sun is 6 degrees below the western geometric horizon after sunset. This is based on the sun being about 24 minutes after sea level sunset in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux, with 18 minutes for 3/4 of a 24-minute mil and 2 minutes for bain hashmashos of Rav Yosi added. It is described as very close to the slightly later 5.95-degree nightfall and rounded up to 6 degrees. The description is based on the opinion of the Baal Hatanya. See [About Our Zmanim Calculations @ Chabad.org](https://www.chabad.org/library/article_cdo/aid/3209349/jewish/About-Our-Zmanim-Calculations.htm). In some northern and southern locations, including places even south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, this zman may not be available if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA18DegreesToFixedLocalChatzos': "The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using the day from dawn to nightfall and counting only the first half of that day. It is based on alos at 18 degrees before sunrise and fixed local chatzos. Sof zman Shema is 3 shaos zmaniyos after alos, which is the midpoint of that half-day. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in far northern or southern locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon, the zman may not be available. This is Rav Moshe Feinstein's opinion of sof zman krias shema according to the Magen Avraham calculation.",
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA16Point1DegreesToFixedLocalChatzos': "The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to Rav Moshe Feinstein's view of the Magen Avraham calculation. It is based on the first half of the day, starting at alos defined as 16.1 degrees and ending at fixed local chatzos. Sof zman Shema is 3 shaos zmaniyos after that alos, or half of this half-day. If the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon, such as in some northern and southern locations beyond the Arctic and Antarctic Circles, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.",
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA90MinutesToFixedLocalChatzos': "The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the Magen Avraham opinion, using Rav Moshe Feinstein's approach of measuring the day from dawn to nightfall based on the first half of the day. The half-day starts at alos 90 minutes before sunrise and ends at fixed local chatzos. Sof zman Shema is 3 shaos zmaniyos after that alos, which is the same as half of this half-day. This zman may not be available in locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for the calculation, such as some northern and southern locations beyond the Arctic and Antarctic Circles.",
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA72MinutesToFixedLocalChatzos': "Rav Moshe Feinstein's opinion of the latest time to recite Shema in the morning, based on the Magen Avraham's view that the day is measured from dawn to nightfall, but using only the first half of the day. The half-day begins at alos, defined as 72 minutes before sunrise, and ends at fixed local chatzos. Sof zman Shema is 3 shaos zmaniyos after that alos, or half of this half-day. Alos is defined as 72 minutes before sunrise, and the half-day ends at fixed local chatzos. At some northern and southern locations, including places south of the Arctic Circle and north of the Antarctic Circle, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated if the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation. See the opinions of [Rav Moshe Feinstein](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moshe_Feinstein) and the [Magen Avraham (MGA)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avraham_Gombiner).",
    'getSofZmanShmaGRASunriseToFixedLocalChatzos': 'The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the GRA-based calculation attributed to Rav Moshe Feinstein, using sunrise-to-fixed-local-chatzos timing. It is calculated as 3 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise, where the day is measured from sunrise until fixed local chatzos. In other words, it is half of that sunrise-to-chatzos half-day. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in some northern or southern locations where the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon, the zman may not be available. See the detailed explanation in the AstronomicalCalendar documentation.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaGRASunriseToFixedLocalChatzos': "The latest time to recite Shacharis according to Rav Moshe Feinstein's approach to the GRA opinion. It is calculated from sunrise to fixed local chatzos, using only the first half of the day. Sof zman tfila is 4 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise, which is 2/3 of that half-day. If the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.",
    'getMinchaGedolaGRAFixedLocalChatzos30Minutes': "Rav Moshe Feinstein's opinion of mincha gedola, the earliest time one can pray mincha according to the GRA, calculated as 30 minutes after fixed local chatzos. 30 minutes after fixed local chatzos. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places and times where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available.",
    'getMinchaKetanaGRAFixedLocalChatzosToSunset': "The time of mincha ketana according to Rav Moshe Feinstein's opinion, calculated according to the GRA. It is 3.5 shaos zmaniyos after fixed local chatzos. This is described as the preferred time to recite the mincha prayers according to the opinion of the Rambam and others. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places such as the Arctic Circle where there are days when the sun does not rise or does not set.",
    'getPlagHaminchaGRAFixedLocalChatzosToSunset': "Rav Moshe Feinstein's opinion of plag hamincha, calculated according to the GRA as 4.75 shaos zmaniyos after fixed local chatzos, with the day ending at sunset. It is calculated as 4.75 proportional hours after fixed local chatzos, using the span from fixed local chatzos to sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places or on days where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available. See the detailed explanation in the AstronomicalCalendar documentation.",
    'getTzais50Minutes': "Tzais, or nightfall, calculated as 50 minutes after sunset. The reference sunset is sea level sunset when elevation is not used, and sunset when elevation is used. 50 minutes after sunset, based on Rabbi Moshe Feinstein's opinion for the New York area. {uses_elevation} This time should not be used for latitudes other than ones similar to the latitude of the New York area. In places such as the Arctic Circle where the sun does not rise or does not set on certain days, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.",
    'getSamuchLeMinchaKetanaGRA': 'The time known as samuch lemincha ketana - the point near mincha ketana when eating or other activity should not begin before praying mincha. It is calculated as 30 minutes before mincha ketana, or equivalently as 9 shaos zmaniyos after the start of the day. The day is measured according to the GRA, from sunrise to sunset. It is 9 times the GRA shaah zmanis after sunrise, or after elevation-adjusted sunrise if elevation is used. If the sun does not reach a low enough position below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. This calculation is described in the context of the GRA day from sunrise to sunset.',
    'getSamuchLeMinchaKetana16Point1Degrees': 'The time of samuch lemincha ketana - the latest time for beginning eating or other activity before praying mincha, based on the 16.1 degrees day. It is calculated as 9 shaos zmaniyos after alos 16.1 degrees. This is also described as half an hour before mincha ketana or 9 shaos zmaniyos after the start of the day. The day is measured from alos 16.1 degrees to tzais 72 minutes. In some extreme northern or southern locations, the zman may not be available because the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation. See the Mechaber and Mishna Berurah 232 and 249:2.',
    'getSamuchLeMinchaKetana72Minutes': 'The time known as samuch lemincha ketana - a point near mincha ketana when eating or other activity should not begin before praying mincha. It is calculated as 9 shaos zmaniyos after alos 72 minutes, using a day that starts at alos 72 minutes and ends at tzais 72 minutes. This is described as half an hour before mincha ketana, or as 9 shaos zmaniyos after the start of the day defined from alos 72 minutes to tzais 72 minutes. The calculation may not be available in northern and southern locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this zman.',
    'getSunsetOrWesternmostSolarAzimuth': "This zman is sunset if sunset occurs. If sunset does not occur, it is the time when the sun reaches its westernmost position, at an azimuth of 270 degrees. It uses sunset when that occurs. If there is no sunset, it uses the moment the sun reaches azimuth 270 degrees, its westernmost position. In polar regions, where there can be days with no sunrise or sunset, this follows the view that the day-night boundary is the sun's westernmost position. This time is close to six hours after astronomical chatzos, but depending on the time of year and location in the Arctic or Antarctic, it can be as much as 46 minutes before or after that time. If neither sunset nor the sun's westernmost azimuth can be determined for the day, the zman may not be available.",
    'getSunriseOrEasternmostSolarAzimuth': 'The zman for sunrise, if sunrise occurs. If sunrise does not occur, it uses the time when the sun reaches its easternmost position, at an azimuth of 90 degrees. Use sunrise when it occurs. If there is no sunrise that day, use the time when the sun is at azimuth 90 degrees. In polar regions, where days without sunrise or sunset can occur, this can serve as the day-night boundary according to the view that sunset is when the sun reaches its westernmost position. This time is close to six hours before astronomical chatzos, but depending on the time of year and location in the Arctic or Antarctic, it can be up to 46 minutes before or after that.',
    'getTzaisGeonim8Point5Degrees': "Nightfall when the sun is 8.5 degrees below the geometric horizon after sunset. This is later than the time for 3 medium stars to appear, and is based on Rabbi Meir Posen's Ohr Meir, which describes 3 small stars being visible. Calculated from the sun's position 8.5 degrees below the geometric zenith after sunset. The source notes that in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux, this is about 36 minutes after sea level sunset. See [Ohr Meir](https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/29283612) and [equinox/equilux zmanim calculations](https://kosherjava.com/2022/01/12/equinox-vs-equilux-zmanim-calculations/). In some far northern or southern locations, including places beyond the Arctic and Antarctic circles, this zman may not be available because the sun may not reach low enough below the horizon.",
    'getAlos16Point1Degrees': "Dawn calculated when the sun is 16.1 degrees below the eastern geometric horizon before sunrise. This uses the idea that dawn to sunrise is 72 minutes, matching 4 mil at 18 minutes per mil. The 16.1-degree figure corresponds to the sun's position 72 minutes before sunrise in Jerusalem around the equinox/equilux. In locations where the sun does not reach low enough below the horizon for this calculation, the zman may not be available. See the detailed explanation on top of the AstronomicalCalendar documentation. See also ComprehensiveZmanimCalendar.getTzais16Point1Degrees().",
    'getAlos72Minutes': 'Alos, or dawn, calculated as 72 minutes before sunrise. This is based on 72 minutes before sunrise, or before sea level sunrise when elevation is used. The 72-minute interval comes from 4 mil at 18 minutes per mil. {uses_elevation} The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places such as the Arctic Circle where the sun does not rise on at least one day of the year and does not set on at least one day of the year. The 72-minute time is based on the view that the Neshef period between dawn and sunrise does not vary by season or location, but depends on the time it takes to walk 4 mil.',
    'getChatzosHayom': 'Astronomical chatzos hayom - the moment the sun transits the local meridian. Calculated as astronomical chatzos, based on sun transit. See [The Definition of Chatzos](https://kosherjava.com/2020/07/02/definition-of-chatzos/) for a detailed explanation of how chatzos is defined.',
    'getChatzosHalayla': 'Chatzos halayla at the end of the day - the last zman of the day, which may actually be after midnight for the day being calculated. Astronomical chatzos halayla for the end of the current day. This can be used, for example, when calculating Erev Pesach so the zman applies to Lail Pesach and can serve as sof zman achilas chametz. See [The Definition of Chatzos](https://kosherjava.com/2020/07/02/definition-of-chatzos/) for a detailed explanation of the different ways chatzos can be understood. If the zman cannot be calculated, it may not be available in situations such as the Arctic Circle where the sun does not rise or set on a given day.',
    'getChatzosHayomAsHalfDay': 'Chatzos calculated as the midpoint between sunrise and sunset. In practice, this is very close to the middle of the day and matches the midpoint of a day defined from alos to tzais when the same offset is used at both ends. Calculated as halfway between sunrise and sunset. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in locations and dates where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available.',
    'getSofZmanShmaGRA': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the GRA. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise, using the GRA day length from sunrise to sunset. The starting and ending points are sea level sunrise and sea level sunset when elevation is not used, or sunrise and sunset when elevation is used. {uses_elevation} If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places where the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getSofZmanShmaMGA72Minutes': 'The latest time to recite morning Shema according to the Magen Avraham, using dawn 72 minutes before sunrise. It is 3 shaos zmaniyos after dawn, with dawn defined as 72 minutes before sunrise. This follows the Magen Avraham view that the day runs from dawn 72 minutes before sunrise to nightfall 72 minutes after sunset. The zman may not be available or cannot be calculated in places where sunrise or sunset does not occur on a given day, such as parts of the Arctic Circle.',
    'getTzais72Minutes': 'Tzais (nightfall) based on the Rabbeinu Tam view that tzais hakochavim is 72 minutes after sunset. It is calculated as 72 standard clock minutes after sunset. Depending on the elevation setting, the countdown starts from either sunset or sea level sunset. The 72 minutes are treated as standard clock minutes any time of year and in any location. The zman may not be available in extreme locations, such as the Arctic Circle, where the sun does not rise or set on at least one day of the year.',
    'getCandleLighting': 'The time for candle lighting, which can be used for any day of the week, including mid-week holidays. It is calculated as the candle-lighting offset minutes before sea level sunset. Elevation adjustments are not included in this zman. If the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated. You can calculate an elevation-adjusted version by using an elevation-adjusted sunset with a time offset calculation.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaGRA': 'The latest time to recite Shema in the morning according to the GRA, based on 4 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise, or after sea level sunrise when elevation is not used. The day is measured from sunrise to sunset, or from sea level sunrise to sea level sunset when elevation is not used. This zman may not be available if the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places where the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day.',
    'getSofZmanTfilaMGA72Minutes': 'The latest time to recite morning shema and related morning prayer by the Magen Avraham calculation. It is 4 shaos zmaniyos after alos 72 minutes. The day is measured from 72 minutes before sunrise to 72 minutes after sunset, with elevation used according to the elevation setting. If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in places and dates where the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getMinchaGedolaGRA': 'The earliest time mincha can be prayed according to the GRA, also called mincha gedola. It is 6.5 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise. The day is measured from sunrise to sunset, or from sea level sunrise to sea level sunset, depending on whether elevation is used. The Rambam prefers waiting until mincha ketana GRA, while the Rash, Tur, GRA, and others hold that mincha may be prayed lechatchila starting at mincha gedola. If the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getMinchaKetanaGRA': 'Mincha ketana, the preferred earliest time to pray mincha according to the Rambam and others. It is 9.5 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise, using sunrise or sea level sunrise depending on elevation settings. The day is measured from sunrise to sunset or from sea level sunrise to sea level sunset, depending on elevation settings. It is based on the GRA calculation. {uses_elevation} If the calculation cannot be computed, such as in locations with days when the sun does not rise or does not set, the zman may not be available or cannot be calculated.',
    'getPlagHaminchaGRA': 'The GRA plag hamincha, which is the earliest time Shabbos can be started. It is calculated as 10.75 shaos zmaniyos after sunrise, using sea level sunrise or sunrise depending on the elevation setting. The day is measured from sea level sunrise to sea level sunset or from sunrise to sunset, depending on the elevation setting. It is based on the GRA. If the zman cannot be calculated, such as in locations where the sun does not rise or does not set on a given day, the zman may not be available.',
}
